Planning exercise (submit before coding layouts)
Draw a route tree like this:

/  → PublicLayout
  ├── index        → Home
  ├── about        → About
  └── events       → Events
/dashboard  → DashboardLayout
  ├── index        → Overview
  ├── profile      → Profile
  └── settings     → Settings
/login     → AuthLayout → Login
/register  → AuthLayout → Register
Answer in writing:

Why should /login not use PublicLayout?
What renders when you visit /dashboard?
What is the purpose of <Outlet />?
Deliverable: Route tree diagram + short written answers (½ page).

Day 2 — Design the three layouts
Before writing much code, design all three layouts. Use Figma, Excalidraw, or pen and paper.

Layout 1: PublicLayout (marketing site)
Sections:

Navbar: Logo “Campus Connect”, links: Home, About, Events, Login button
Main: <Outlet /> for page content
Footer: Copyright, quick links, contact email
Design notes:

Clean, welcoming, light background
Full-width hero area on Home
Navbar sticky at top
Layout 2: DashboardLayout (app shell)
Sections:

Sidebar (left): Logo, nav links: Overview, Profile, Settings, Logout (fake)
Header (top): Page title area + user avatar placeholder
Main: <Outlet /> for dashboard pages
Design notes:

Sidebar fixed on desktop; collapses to hamburger on mobile
Different color scheme from public site (e.g. darker sidebar)
Active sidebar link clearly highlighted
Layout 3: AuthLayout (login/register)
Sections:

Centered card on a simple background
Logo at top of card
<Outlet /> inside card for Login or Register form
Small link below card: “Back to home”
Design notes:

No navbar, no footer, no sidebar
Minimal distractions
Same card wrapper for both Login and Register
Deliverable: 3 wireframes (one per layout) + 2–3 sentences explaining your design choices.

